  "prompt": "What is indirect recursion?",
  "response": "Indirect recursion occurs when a function calls another function, which eventually leads back to the original function. This forms a cycle of function calls that can continue indefinitely if not properly managed. Indirect recursion involves two or more functions that call each other in a circular manner.\n\nHere's a simple example to illustrate indirect recursion:\n\n```python\ndef function_a(x):\n    if x > 0:\n        print(\"Function A:\", x)\n        function_b(x - 1)\n\ndef function_b(x):\n    if x > 0:\n        print(\"Function B:\", x)\n        function_a(x - 1)\n\n# Start the recursion chain\nfunction_a(5)\n```\n\nIn this example:\n1. `function_a` calls `function_b`.\n2. `function_b` calls `function_a`.\n\nThe recursion continues until the base condition (`x > 0`) is no longer satisfied. Indirect recursion can be more complex and involve more functions, but the principle remains the same: functions call each other in a cycle. It's crucial to have a base condition to prevent infinite recursion and potential stack overflow errors.",
